WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.034
Place three observations on our evidence bench.

00:00:03.034 --> 00:00:05.635
A wooden block keeps its shape.

00:00:05.635 --> 00:00:08.670
Water takes the shape of its cup.

00:00:08.670 --> 00:00:10.404
Air fills a balloon.

00:00:10.404 --> 00:00:12.572
We can observe each behaviour.

00:00:12.572 --> 00:00:16.040
Now we need an explanation that connects them.

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:18.208
Scientists use a particle model.

00:00:18.208 --> 00:00:21.243
It treats matter as tiny moving pieces.

00:00:21.243 --> 00:00:24.277
Notice the order: evidence first, model second.

00:00:24.277 --> 00:00:27.312
The colourful dots are not the evidence.

00:00:27.312 --> 00:00:33.381
A useful model should explain several observations and help us predict a new result.

00:00:33.381 --> 00:00:36.416
It should also have a clear limit.

00:00:36.416 --> 00:00:40.752
Our simple model cannot show every detail of real particles.

00:00:46.252 --> 00:00:47.839
Start with the block.

00:00:47.839 --> 00:00:54.984
In our solid model, particles are close together and remain in mostly fixed positions relative to their neighbours.

00:00:54.984 --> 00:00:58.953
They are not perfectly still; we show a small vibration.

00:00:58.953 --> 00:01:05.304
This arrangement helps explain why the block keeps its own shape and is difficult to squash.

00:01:05.304 --> 00:01:10.464
The particles are already close, so there is little empty space to remove.

00:01:10.464 --> 00:01:18.799
The model does not say every solid is hard: rubber can bend, and a sponge is solid material with air spaces.

00:01:18.799 --> 00:01:22.371
The picture explains a broad pattern, not every property.

00:01:23.772 --> 00:01:27.645
Pour water from a short cup into a wide bowl.

00:01:27.645 --> 00:01:31.519
Its shape changes, but the water still takes up space.

00:01:31.519 --> 00:01:36.556
In the liquid model, particles stay close together and slide past one another.

00:01:36.556 --> 00:01:39.267
This helps explain flow and changing shape.

00:01:39.267 --> 00:01:45.078
It also explains why a sealed syringe full of water is very hard to push.

00:01:45.078 --> 00:01:47.403
The particles are already close together.

00:01:47.403 --> 00:01:51.276
Do not picture each particle as a tiny wet drop.

00:01:51.276 --> 00:01:55.925
Wetness is a property we notice when many water particles act together.

00:01:55.925 --> 00:01:58.250
Our dots show spacing and movement.

00:01:58.250 --> 00:02:02.123
They do not show the real shapes of water molecules.

00:02:03.524 --> 00:02:07.867
Now consider air trapped in a capped syringe with no needle.

00:02:07.867 --> 00:02:12.605
When the plunger is pressed gently, the trapped air occupies less space.

00:02:12.605 --> 00:02:15.764
Release it, and the plunger can move back.

00:02:15.764 --> 00:02:21.293
In our gas model, particles are much farther apart than in solids and liquids,

00:02:21.293 --> 00:02:24.451
moving in many directions through the available space.

00:02:24.451 --> 00:02:27.610
Pressing the plunger does not shrink each particle.

00:02:27.610 --> 00:02:29.980
It reduces the spaces between them.

00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:31.164
That distinction matters.

00:02:31.164 --> 00:02:36.692
Use only a classroom syringe designed for demonstrations, keep it pointed away from faces,

00:02:36.692 --> 00:02:39.851
and press gently with the outlet securely capped.

00:02:39.851 --> 00:02:45.379
Never use a needle, never trap reactive materials, and never force a stuck plunger.

00:02:50.879 --> 00:02:52.890
Compare two identical capped syringes.

00:02:52.890 --> 00:02:54.097
One holds air.

00:02:54.097 --> 00:02:56.912
An adult fills the other with water.

00:02:56.912 --> 00:03:00.532
A gentle push moves the air plunger much farther.

00:03:00.532 --> 00:03:02.945
The particle model explains the difference.

00:03:02.945 --> 00:03:05.761
Gas particles have large gaps between them.

00:03:05.761 --> 00:03:08.174
Liquid particles are already close together.

00:03:08.174 --> 00:03:12.598
At this level, we say liquids are very hard to compress.

00:03:12.598 --> 00:03:17.827
This does not mean there is no space at all between liquid particles.

00:03:17.827 --> 00:03:19.436
Never force either syringe.

00:03:19.436 --> 00:03:23.055
The fair comparison changes one thing: air or water.

00:03:23.055 --> 00:03:27.479
The clear difference gives our spacing model useful evidence to explain.

00:03:28.879 --> 00:03:36.127
Imagine an adult opens a small container with a scented cotton pad in a ventilated room.

00:03:36.127 --> 00:03:40.656
After a while, someone farther away may notice the scent.

00:03:40.656 --> 00:03:42.921
Nobody stirred the whole room.

00:03:42.921 --> 00:03:46.544
Scent particles moved and mixed with air particles.

00:03:46.544 --> 00:03:48.809
This gradual spreading is diffusion.

00:03:48.809 --> 00:03:51.979
More scent particles begin near the container.

00:03:51.979 --> 00:03:56.509
Over time, they spread into places with fewer scent particles.

00:03:56.509 --> 00:03:59.679
The particle model helps explain the pattern.

00:03:59.679 --> 00:04:06.474
Use an animation unless a teacher has checked for allergies and approved a mild scent.

00:04:06.474 --> 00:04:08.738
Never sniff any chemical directly.

00:04:08.738 --> 00:04:15.080
Our noses detect the scent, but they do not let us see the particles.

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:18.648
Diffusion also happens in liquids.

00:04:18.648 --> 00:04:22.550
Place one drop of food colouring into still water.

00:04:22.550 --> 00:04:25.152
Watch from the side without stirring.

00:04:25.152 --> 00:04:28.621
The colour slowly spreads beyond its starting point.

00:04:28.621 --> 00:04:34.258
Our model says moving water and colouring particles become more mixed over time.

00:04:34.258 --> 00:04:39.028
However, visible swirls may also come from currents in the water.

00:04:39.028 --> 00:04:42.931
Those currents can be caused by small temperature differences.

00:04:42.931 --> 00:04:49.002
This is the scene's one important limit: the cup does not show diffusion alone.

00:04:49.002 --> 00:04:55.940
Scientists improve the check by keeping temperature steady, repeating the trial and recording what they see.

00:04:55.940 --> 00:05:01.144
One attractive pattern is useful evidence, but it is not complete proof.

00:05:06.644 --> 00:05:08.408
Focus on the pattern.

00:05:08.408 --> 00:05:13.259
At first, many colouring particles are crowded into one small region.

00:05:13.259 --> 00:05:16.346
They move and collide with water particles.

00:05:16.346 --> 00:05:19.874
Over time, the colouring becomes more evenly spread.

00:05:19.874 --> 00:05:24.284
Scientists call the crowded region a region of higher concentration.

00:05:24.284 --> 00:05:27.812
Places with fewer colouring particles have lower concentration.

00:05:27.812 --> 00:05:31.781
The overall spread goes from higher to lower concentration.

00:05:31.781 --> 00:05:36.191
Individual particles do not follow straight orders towards empty spaces.

00:05:36.191 --> 00:05:37.955
Their paths are irregular.

00:05:37.955 --> 00:05:42.806
The even spread is the large result of all that motion.

00:05:42.806 --> 00:05:46.334
Particles still move after the colour looks even.

00:05:46.334 --> 00:05:52.507
The main limit is that our neat animation makes real collisions look much simpler.

00:05:53.908 --> 00:05:58.415
A model becomes stronger when it makes a useful prediction.

00:05:58.415 --> 00:06:04.726
Suppose one drop of colouring enters two identical cups, one shallow and one tall,

00:06:04.726 --> 00:06:07.881
at the same temperature with no stirring.

00:06:07.881 --> 00:06:10.586
Which will look evenly coloured first?

00:06:10.586 --> 00:06:14.192
Consider distance, currents and container shape, then test.

00:06:14.192 --> 00:06:21.404
The shallow cup offers a shorter vertical distance, but real water movement can complicate the result.

00:06:21.404 --> 00:06:27.714
A careful prediction names the pattern and conditions: if temperature and disturbance are controlled,

00:06:27.714 --> 00:06:33.124
colouring should gradually spread in both cups, although mixing times may differ.

00:06:34.524 --> 00:06:36.542
Collect the explanatory wins.

00:06:36.542 --> 00:06:42.092
Close, mostly fixed particles help explain why a solid keeps shape.

00:06:42.092 --> 00:06:48.146
Close, sliding particles help explain why a liquid flows but resists compression.

00:06:48.146 --> 00:06:56.219
Widely spaced moving particles help explain why a gas fills available space and can be compressed.

00:06:56.219 --> 00:06:59.750
Constant motion and mixing help explain diffusion.

00:06:59.750 --> 00:07:05.805
The model connects several observations, but the animation itself is not evidence.

00:07:05.805 --> 00:07:10.850
Evidence came from the investigations; the animation is our representation.

00:07:10.850 --> 00:07:19.427
If future evidence does not fit, scientists adjust or replace the model rather than ignoring the observation.

00:07:20.827 --> 00:07:22.828
Now reveal three drawing conventions.

00:07:22.828 --> 00:07:25.629
First, the dots are far too large.

00:07:25.629 --> 00:07:29.231
Real particles are much smaller compared with the container.

00:07:29.231 --> 00:07:33.233
Second, the bright colours are labels chosen by the artist.

00:07:33.233 --> 00:07:35.634
They are not real particle colours.

00:07:35.634 --> 00:07:37.634
Third, the arrows simplify motion.

00:07:37.634 --> 00:07:40.836
Real particles collide and change direction many times.

00:07:40.836 --> 00:07:42.836
Stop after those three reveals.

00:07:42.836 --> 00:07:47.238
The model has one clear job: compare spacing, arrangement and motion.

00:07:47.238 --> 00:07:50.840
It does not show exact particle appearance or scale.

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:54.041
The word particle is also a broad label.

00:07:54.041 --> 00:08:00.043
It may mean an atom or a molecule, depending on the substance we are modelling.

00:08:05.543 --> 00:08:08.960
Listen to four claims and repair each one.

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:15.794
'Gas has no matter' becomes 'gas is matter whose particles are widely spaced in this model.

00:08:15.794 --> 00:08:21.347
' 'A compressed gas has crushed particles' becomes 'compression mainly reduces the gaps.

00:08:21.347 --> 00:08:27.754
' 'Liquid particles are wet drops' becomes 'wetness describes many particles interacting at a surface,

00:08:27.754 --> 00:08:29.462
not one drawn dot.

00:08:29.462 --> 00:08:37.577
' 'Diffusion happens because particles want to spread out' becomes 'irregular particle motion and collisions produce an overall spread.

00:08:37.577 --> 00:08:41.849
' Good explanations do more than mark a statement wrong.

00:08:41.849 --> 00:08:45.693
They replace it with a mechanism connected to evidence.

00:08:45.693 --> 00:08:50.391
Notice also that we say the model suggests or helps explain.

00:08:50.391 --> 00:08:55.943
We do not pretend a Grade 4 drawing contains the whole microscopic story.

00:08:57.344 --> 00:09:03.688
A sealed flexible bag looks almost empty, but when squeezed, another part bulges.

00:09:03.688 --> 00:09:05.640
Is there matter inside?

00:09:05.640 --> 00:09:06.128
Yes.

00:09:06.128 --> 00:09:11.008
The shape change suggests trapped gas moving through available space.

00:09:11.008 --> 00:09:17.352
Our model shows widely spaced moving particles, but not the exact gas mixture,

00:09:17.352 --> 00:09:20.768
molecular shapes or forces in the plastic.

00:09:20.768 --> 00:09:23.696
Compare a sealed bag of water.

00:09:23.696 --> 00:09:30.040
It changes outer shape, but its volume changes very little under gentle pressure.

00:09:30.040 --> 00:09:35.408
The contrast connects flow, space and compression without seeing individual particles.

00:09:36.807 --> 00:09:40.321
Design a low-risk investigation for one model prediction.

00:09:40.321 --> 00:09:47.788
Choose the question: does one drop of colouring spread differently in still water at two safe temperatures?

00:09:47.788 --> 00:09:53.058
An adult prepares cool and comfortably warm tap water, never hot water.

00:09:53.058 --> 00:10:00.524
Use identical clear cups, equal water amounts, the same colouring, one drop placed in the same position,

00:10:00.524 --> 00:10:01.842
and no stirring.

00:10:01.842 --> 00:10:04.477
Record photographs at equal time intervals.

00:10:04.477 --> 00:10:10.187
Temperature is the planned difference; cup shape, volume and drop size are controlled.

00:10:10.187 --> 00:10:15.896
Even then, convection currents can affect the result, so repeat and report variation.

00:10:15.896 --> 00:10:19.849
The goal is not to force a tidy answer.

00:10:19.849 --> 00:10:25.120
It is to gather evidence that can challenge or refine our explanation.

00:10:26.519 --> 00:10:29.716
Finish every particle explanation with three parts.

00:10:29.716 --> 00:10:34.740
First, name the evidence: trapped air becomes smaller under gentle pressure.

00:10:34.740 --> 00:10:42.046
Second, use the model: gas particles are widely spaced, so compression reduces the gaps between them.

00:10:42.046 --> 00:10:50.723
Third, name a limit: the dots are not to scale and do not show exact particle shapes or forces.

00:10:50.723 --> 00:10:53.463
Try the same frame for diffusion.

00:10:53.463 --> 00:10:56.203
Evidence: colouring spreads through still water.

00:10:56.203 --> 00:10:59.857
Model: moving particles become more mixed over time.

00:10:59.857 --> 00:11:05.793
Limit: visible currents may also move the water, and the animation simplifies collisions.

00:11:05.793 --> 00:11:09.903
This evidence-model-limit pattern keeps our science useful and honest.

00:11:09.903 --> 00:11:15.384
You are ready to explain observations without mistaking the drawing for reality.
